🛠 Prerequisites
- Docker installed and running
- kubectl installed and configured

👉Recommended resource allocation for running a Vind cluster (1 master + 2 workers) on Docker Desktop (Windows):
- Master Node (Control Plane) → 2 vCPUs, 4 GB RAM
- Each Worker Node → 2 vCPUs, 3–4 GB RAM
- Cluster Total (1 master + 2 workers) → 6 vCPUs, 8–10 GB RAM


👉Install kubectl (if not already):

curl -LO "https://dl.k8s.io/release/$(curl -L -s https://dl.k8s.io/release/stable.txt)/bin/windows/amd64/kubectl.exe"
mv kubectl.exe /c/Users/myuser/bin/
export PATH=$PATH:/c/Users/myuser/bin

👉Download vCluster CLI:
curl -L -o vcluster.exe https://github.com/loft-sh/vcluster/releases/latest/download/vcluster-windows-amd64.exe

👉Move Binary to PATH
mv vcluster.exe /c/Users/Windows/bin/
export PATH=$PATH:/c/Users/Windows/bin

👉Reload your shell
source ~/.bashrc

👉Check version
vcluster --version

👉Set driver as docker
vcluster use driver docker

👉Create Vind cluster:
vcluster create vind-cluster 


👉Create multiple nodes using kind
Create a Kind config file

kind: Cluster
apiVersion: kind.x-k8s.io/v1alpha4
nodes:
  - role: control-plane
  - role: worker
  - role: worker
  - role: worker

👉Create the vCluster with Kind

vcluster create mycluster --driver=kind --config kind-config.yaml

👉Connect to cluster:
vcluster connect mycluster

👉Verify nodes:
kubectl get nodes

vcluster list
👉To access UI
vcluster platform start
